    "plan_content": "Here's a summary of the plan I've written:\n\n---\n\n## Plan: Add `next/geo` Utility Module\n\n### What I found by reading the codebase\n\n- **`server.js`** uses a dual CJS export: builds a named object, sets `module.exports = serverExports`, then also does `exports.X = serverExports.X` for each name (for ESM `import { x }` compatibility)\n- **`server.d.ts`** uses `export { Name } from 'next/dist/...'` named re-exports\n- **`user-agent.ts`** exports an `interface` + functions with `export function`, using `{ headers }: { headers: Headers }` destructuring — the exact pattern to follow\n- Existing tests use **Jest** (`describe`, `it`, `expect`) — no new test framework needed\n- `package.json` `files` array: `\"geo.js\"` / `\"geo.d.ts\"` belong after `\"form.d.ts\"` alphabetically (f → g)\n\n### 5 files to create/modify\n\n| # | File | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.ts` | **Create** — core implementation |\n| 2 | `packages/next/geo.js` | **Create** — dual CJS entry point |\n| 3 | `packages/next/geo.d.ts` | **Create** — TypeScript declarations |\n| 4 | `packages/next/package.json` | **Edit** — add `\"geo.js\"`, `\"geo.d.ts\"` to `files` |\n| 5 | `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.test.ts` | **Create** — Jest unit tests |\n\n### Key design decisions\n- `extractGeo(headers)` private helper shared by both `geo()` and `geoFromHeaders()` (no duplication)\n- `headers.get() ?? undefined` converts `null` → `undefined` for strict-mode TypeScript interface compatibility\n- `cf-ipcountry` (Cloudflare) is the fallback when `x-vercel-ip-country` is absent\n- Haversine formula in `geoDistance()` — pure math, no external deps",
